    "main_cast = [\"Monica\", \"Rachel\", \"Phoebe\", \"Joey\", \"Chandler\", \"Ross\"]\n",
    "labels = {node: node for node in main_cast if node in G_unweighted.nodes()}\n",
    "\n",
    "nx.draw_networkx_nodes(\n",
    "    G_unweighted,\n",
    "    pos,\n",
    "    nodelist=list(labels.keys()),\n",
    "    node_size=300,\n",
    "    node_color=\"#e76f51\",\n",
    "    edgecolors=\"black\",\n",
    "    linewidths=0.7,\n",
    ")\n",
    "nx.draw_networkx_labels(pos=pos, G=G_unweighted, labels=labels, font_size=10)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title(\"Friends Interaction Network - Main Cast Highlighted\")\n",
    "plt.axis(\"off\")\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ff03bb5d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **Graph Analysis**\n",
    "\n",
    "The main cast sits near the visual core and carries many of the thickest ties. Peripheral characters appear around that center with thinner, more localized links. The figure therefore supports the numerical baseline: the Friends network is sparse overall, but organized around a very strong central ensemble.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2eaa9c73",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## **Week 2**\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c8d8293c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **2.1 Largest Connected Component**\n",
    "\n",
    "For clustering analysis, we work on the largest connected component so all nodes are part of the same reachable structure. In the book's terminology, a disconnected network is composed of connected components, and the largest one is the giant component.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "a11836d2",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2026-05-05T20:26:13.872132Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2026-05-05T20:26:13.872132Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2026-05-05T20:26:13.924516Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2026-05-05T20:26:13.924516Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def largest_component_graph(G: nx.Graph) -> nx.Graph:\n",
    "    \"\"\"Return largest connected component as a copy.\"\"\"\n",
    "    if G.number_of_nodes() == 0:\n",
    "        return G.copy()\n",
    "    lcc_nodes = max(nx.connected_components(G), key=len)\n",
    "    return G.subgraph(lcc_nodes).copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "G_week2 = largest_component_graph(nx.Graph(G_unweighted))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "11ce08fa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **Interpretation**\n",
    "\n",
    "Restricting to the largest component avoids isolated-fragment artifacts and keeps the denominator of all clustering calculations meaningful. In this dataset, it also keeps the main cast and the large majority of recurring social structure in one common graph domain.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "73d5f3a9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **2.2 Local Clustering**\n",
    "\n",
    "We compute local clustering manually and compare it against NetworkX for each node. The book defines the clustering coefficient of node `i` as the fraction of pairs of `i`'s neighbors that are connected to each other:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "C(i)=\\frac{\\tau(i)}{\\tau_{max}(i)}=\\frac{\\tau(i)}{\\binom{k_i}{2}}=\\frac{2\\tau(i)}{k_i(k_i-1)}\n",
    "$$\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "b60eba53",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2026-05-05T20:26:13.932660Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2026-05-05T20:26:13.932660Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.066067Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.065525Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def clustering_per_node_manual(G: nx.Graph) -> dict[str, float]:\n",
    "    \"\"\"Manual local clustering coefficient for each node.\"\"\"\n",
    "    output = {}\n",
    "    for node in G.nodes():\n",
    "        neigh = list(G.neighbors(node))\n",
    "        k = len(neigh)\n",
    "        if k < 2:\n",
    "            output[node] = 0.0\n",
    "            continue\n",
    "\n",
    "        closed_triplets = 0\n",
    "        for i, u in enumerate(neigh):\n",
    "            for v in neigh[i + 1 :]:\n",
    "                if G.has_edge(u, v):\n",
    "                    closed_triplets += 1\n",
    "\n",
    "        output[node] = (2.0 * closed_triplets) / (k * (k - 1))\n",
    "    return output\n",
    "\n",
    "manual_local = clustering_per_node_manual(G_week2)\n",
    "nx_local = nx.clustering(G_week2)\n",
    "\n",
    "comparison = pd.DataFrame(\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"manual\": pd.Series(manual_local),\n",
    "        \"networkx\": pd.Series(nx_local),\n",
    "    }\n",
    ")\n",
    "comparison[\"abs_diff\"] = (comparison[\"manual\"] - comparison[\"networkx\"]).abs()\n",
    "\n",
    "display(comparison.sort_values(\"abs_diff\", ascending=False).head(10))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1f3b0139",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **Interpretation**\n",
    "\n",
    "The manual implementation matches NetworkX exactly up to numerical precision. This matters because the later distributional analysis depends on the clustering values, not just the average. The top rows shown are not errors; they simply confirm that even highly visible nodes have zero absolute difference between implementations.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8ff2b03b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **2.3 Average Clustering and Transitivity**\n",
    "\n",
    "We aggregate local closure and compare it with global triadic closure. The book defines the clustering coefficient of the entire network as the average of node clustering coefficients over nodes with degree greater than one:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "C=\\frac{\\sum_{i:k_i>1} C(i)}{N_{k>1}}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Transitivity is still reported as a NetworkX comparison metric, but no separate displayed formula is used here because the book section we follow introduces clustering through `C(i)` and `C`.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "bc997dde",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.072015Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.072015Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.234061Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.231951Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def average_clustering_manual(G: nx.Graph) -> float:\n",
    "    coeffs = clustering_per_node_manual(G)\n",
    "    return float(np.mean(list(coeffs.values())))\n",
    "\n",
    "manual_avg = average_clustering_manual(G_week2)\n",
    "nx_avg = nx.average_clustering(G_week2)\n",
    "nx_transitivity = nx.transitivity(G_week2)\n",
    "\n",
    "stats_week2 = pd.Series(\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"manual_average_clustering\": manual_avg,\n",
    "        \"networkx_average_clustering\": nx_avg,\n",
    "        \"networkx_transitivity\": nx_transitivity,\n",
    "        \"max_abs_node_diff\": comparison[\"abs_diff\"].max(),\n",
    "    }\n",
    ")\n",
    "display(stats_week2.to_frame(\"value\"))\n",
    "\n",
    "assert comparison[\"abs_diff\"].max() < 1e-12\n",
    "assert abs(manual_avg - nx_avg) < 1e-12"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "52d8fccf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **Interpretation**\n",
    "\n",
    "Average clustering is about **0.50**, while transitivity is only about **0.034**. This contrast is important: many small peripheral neighborhoods are fully or nearly closed, but the global graph is dominated by high-degree central characters whose many possible triangles are not all closed. Local closure is therefore high, while global closure remains low.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "25090f52",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## **Week 3**\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ccbc7342",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **3.1 Average Neighbor Clustering**\n",
    "\n",
    "For each node, we compute the average clustering coefficient of its neighbors. This is an assignment-specific comparison derived from the clustering values above, so we describe it in prose rather than introducing an extra formula not shown in the book.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "a1c6b63b",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.238575Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.238575Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.264426Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.263552Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def neighbor_avg_clustering(\n",
    "    G: nx.Graph, clustering_dict: dict[str, float]\n",
    ") -> dict[str, float]:\n",
    "    out = {}\n",
    "    for node in G.nodes():\n",
    "        neigh = list(G.neighbors(node))\n",
    "        if not neigh:\n",
    "            out[node] = 0.0\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            out[node] = float(np.mean([clustering_dict[n] for n in neigh]))\n",
    "    return out\n",
    "\n",
    "neighbor_average = neighbor_avg_clustering(G_week2, manual_local)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "76135b7a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **Interpretation**\n",
    "\n",
    "This metric shifts the question from a node's own closed triangles to the social environment around it. A character can have low personal clustering while still being connected to tightly clustered neighbors, which is common in core-periphery story networks.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "efc08e2b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **3.2 CDF Comparison**\n",
    "\n",
    "We compare the cumulative distributions of node clustering and average neighbor clustering. The book introduces cumulative distributions as a way to compare how broadly a network quantity varies across nodes, so we keep the focus on the plotted distributions rather than adding a separate empirical-CDF formula.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "28644fd2",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.271922Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.264426Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.525869Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2026-05-05T20:26:14.525869Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def empirical_cdf(values) -> tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray]:\n",
    "    arr = np.asarray(list(values), dtype=float)\n",
    "    if arr.size == 0:\n",
    "        return np.array([]), np.array([])\n",
    "    x = np.sort(arr)\n",
    "    y = np.arange(1, len(x) + 1) / len(x)\n",
    "    return x, y\n",
    "\n",
    "x1, y1 = empirical_cdf(manual_local.values())\n",
    "x2, y2 = empirical_cdf(neighbor_average.values())\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "plt.step(x1, y1, where=\"post\", linewidth=2, color=\"#1d3557\", label=\"node clustering\")\n",
    "plt.step(\n",
    "    x2,\n",
    "    y2,\n",
    "    where=\"post\",\n",
    "    linewidth=2,\n",
    "    color=\"#e63946\",\n",
    "    label=\"neighbor-average clustering\",\n",
    ")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"clustering value\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"cumulative probability\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"Week 3 - Cumulative Distributions\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6c94f39a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **Graph Analysis**\n",
    "\n",
    "The two CDFs describe different structural views. Node clustering has many extreme values because small supporting-character neighborhoods can be perfectly closed. Neighbor-average clustering is smoother and lower for many nodes, showing that proximity to the main cast often means being attached to broad, less closed neighborhoods.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "64bf5999",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **3.3 Quantile Summary**\n",
    "\n",
    "We summarize both distributions at quartile levels. The quartile table is a compact numerical companion to the cumulative-distribution plot, so no additional displayed formula is needed.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "01b7ae84",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
